======================================================================
PART 4: WHY H=21 IS PERMANENTLY FORBIDDEN
======================================================================

H = 1 + 2*a1 + 4*a2 + 8*a3 + ... + 2^k*a_k = 21
=> sum 2^j * a_j = 20  (j from 1)

Key constraint: a_k > 0 implies a_(k-1) >= C(k,2)*a_k/...
More precisely: an independent k-set in Omega contains
C(k,2) disjoint pairs, so a2 >= C(k,2) when a_k >= 1.

For any k >= 1:
  If a_k >= 1, the k cycles use >= 3k vertices
  Their C(k,2) pairs are disjoint, so a2 >= C(k,2)
  Minimum contribution: 2^k + 4*C(k,2)
  k=1: min contribution = 2^1 + 4*C(1,2) = 2 + 0 = 2
  k=2: min contribution = 2^2 + 4*C(2,2) = 4 + 4 = 8
  k=3: min contribution = 2^3 + 4*C(3,2) = 8 + 12 = 20
  k=4: min contribution = 2^4 + 4*C(4,2) = 16 + 24 = 40
         > 20 = H-1. So a_4 = 0 forced for k >= 4.

  Maximum non-zero coefficient: a_3
  For H=21: only a_1 and a_2 can be non-zero (same as quadratic era!)
  Back to: a1 + 2*a2 = 10, which we proved impossible at n=7.
  But at n>=9, new (a1, a2) pairs might become achievable!
  Need to check: is (a1=10, a2=0) achievable at any n?

  (a1=10, a2=0): 10 odd cycles, all sharing vertices
  At n=7: impossible (c3+c5+c7 never = 10 with all conflicting)
  At n=9: more cycles available (c3 up to C(9,3)/7=12)
  Could in principle work... but need ALL to pairwise conflict!
  With 10 cycles and 0 disjoint pairs, every pair must share a vertex.

======================================================================
PART 5: CONSTRUCTED n=9 WITH 3 DISJOINT 3-CYCLES
======================================================================

  Block-circulant tournament: blocks {0,1,2}, {3,4,5}, {6,7,8}
  H = 3159
  c3 = 30
  Has 3 disjoint 3-cycles? True
  Triple: [{0, 1, 2}, {3, 4, 5}, {8, 6, 7}]
  Score sequence: [np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4), np.int64(4)]

  If a3 >= 1: a2 >= C(3,2) = 3 (from the triple)
  Minimum H with a3=1: H >= 1 + 0 + 4*3 + 8*1 = 21
  But H = 21 is forbidden! So what gives?
  Answer: a1 is at least 3 (the three cycles themselves)
  H >= 1 + 2*3 + 4*3 + 8*1 = 1 + 6 + 12 + 8 = 27
  So a3=1 forces H >= 27, safely above 21.

  More precisely: a3=1 requires a1 >= 3, a2 >= 3
  Minimum H = 1 + 2*3 + 4*3 + 8*1 = 27
  H=21 would need a1+2*a2+4*a3 = 10 with a3>=1, a2>=3, a1>=3
  a1 + 2*3 + 4*1 = 10 => a1 = 0. But a1 >= 3 (contradiction!)
  H=21 is PERMANENTLY FORBIDDEN by this argument.

======================================================================
SUMMARY
======================================================================

  n=8: alpha(Omega) <= 2 (quadratic I.P. only)
  n=9: alpha(Omega) = 3 first possible (82.0% of random)
  H=7: permanently forbidden (a1+2*a2 = 3, too small for any a_k>0)
  H=21: permanently forbidden (a3>=1 forces a1>=3, a2>=3 => H>=27)
  The cubic coefficient a3 contributes 2^3 = 8 per independent triple
  The 8 = 2^3 from Cayley-Dickson maps exactly to the OCF weight
